## Historical and Philosophical Context

The distinction between direct and indirect taxation is not merely academic; it has sparked revolutions, toppled governments, and ruined countless dinner conversations. Historically, the ability of a government to levy a direct tax was a measure of its power and reach. It required a robust administrative apparatus capable of assessing wealth, tracking individuals, and compelling payment—a level of intimacy that many subjects and citizens found, and still find, deeply intrusive.

Philosophers and economists have long debated the merits of each system. Proponents of direct taxation often argue that it is a more transparent and progressive system, as it can be tailored to an individual's ability to pay. It forces a direct confrontation with the cost of governance. Critics, however, point to its potential for discouraging productivity and investment. Why build a taller tower if the king gets to claim every tenth brick?

